We list $\mathbb{Z}$ as follows: $0, 1, -1, 2, -2, 3, -3, \ldots$

Formally, define $f: \mathbb{N} \to \mathbb{Z}$ by
\[
f(n) = \begin{cases}
n/2 & \text{if } n \text{ is even} \\
-(n-1)/2 & \text{if } n \text{ is odd}
\end{cases}
\]
(using the convention $\mathbb{N} = \{1, 2, 3, \ldots\}$ and mapping 
$1 \mapsto 0$, $2 \mapsto 1$, $3 \mapsto -1$, etc.).

